---
description: Python coding conventions for this workspace
globs: **/*.py
alwaysApply: false
---

1. Don't use import statements inside functions, unless it actually needs to be there. Put imports at the top of the file. Use separate sections for stdlib modules, third-party modules and local modules. Sort each section alphabetically.
2. Use `pathlib` for all path related operations, whenever possible.
3. Use f-strings for string formatting whenever possible.
4. Use type hints whenever possible.
5. Function arguments and return value should use a single type when possible. Try not to mix types.
6. Code files (i.e. `.py` files) should document the abstractions being used, focusing on the "why". Readers of the code should be able to read docstrings or comments to get a high-level overview of why the code is organized the way it is.
7. For scripts, arguments that users can *reasonably expect to modify* should be exposed using argparse, with suitable defaults. Don't use module level vars for specifying defaults in such cases.
